By next-generation sequencing, between 13,214 and 26,259 reads were obtained of each analyzed sample of which at least 93% passed quality check and was further analyzed in a virus discovery pipeline (Table 1
). Compared to other samples that were analyzed in the same sequencing run, a similar number of reads was obtained, although the number of large sequence reads was somewhat reduced (Fig. 1
). Reads were analysed by BLASTN and BLASTX analysis and categorized according to their taxonomy. Most reads detected in the ferret tissues were categorized as eukaryotic sequences (66% and 69%). Most reads detected in the gull tissues were categorized as unknown (48% both tissues) while also a substantial proportion was categorized as eukaryotic sequence (35% both tissues) (Table 2
).
